## 6. Multi-Page Generation Analysis

### **Three Generation Modes:**

| Mode | Description | Token Cost | Character Consistency |
|------|-------------|-----------|----------------------|
| **Panel-by-panel** | Generate 1 panel at a time | Highest (per-call overhead) | Best (full control per panel) |
| **Full Page** | Generate N panels in one page (e.g. 3-6 panels) | Medium | Good (single batch, shared context) |
| **Multi-Page** | Generate multiple pages (e.g. 3-5 pages Ã— 4-5 panels each) in one go | **Lowest** | Depends on model capability |

### **Feasibility Analysis with Nano Banana:**

**Panel-by-panel (current approach):**
- Token cost: ~1 API call per panel. For 20 panels = 20 calls
- Character consistency: Best because you can pass character reference image per call
- User control: Maximum

**Full Page generation (recommended to add):**
- Send all panel descriptions for a single page in one prompt
- The AI generates a complete manga page layout (e.g., 4 panels arranged vertically)
- Token cost: ~1 call per page instead of ~4-5 calls per page = **75-80% savings**
- Character consistency: Good â€” all panels share the same generation context
- This is what Comica and most AI comic tools do

**Multi-Page batch (ambitious but possible):**
- Send entire chapter/episode worth of panel descriptions
- AI generates 3-5 complete pages in one session
- Token cost: **Maximum savings** (1 call for 15-25 panels)
- Character consistency: Harder â€” the model may drift across pages
- Reality check: Current image generation models (including Nano Banana) generate **one image per call**. To do "multi-page in one go" you'd need:
  - Option A: Sequential API calls with shared character embedding (still multiple calls, but automated)
  - Option B: A model that supports multi-image output (very few do this well)
  - Option C: Batch queue with shared LoRA/character context across calls

### **Realistic Recommendation:**

**Add TWO generation modes:**

1. **ğŸ¯ Panel Mode** (existing) â€” Generate individual panels with maximum control
2. **ğŸ“„ Page Mode** (new) â€” User defines a page with N panels (descriptions, characters, dialogue for each), system generates the full page as a single composed image with proper manga layout

**For Page Mode with Nano Banana:**
- Compose a single prompt that describes the entire page layout (e.g., "A 4-panel manga page, top panel shows X, second panel shows Y...")
- Nano Banana can generate a single image that IS the entire page
- This is genuinely 1 API call = 4-5 panels worth of content
- Character consistency is inherently better because it's all one image generation

**Multi-page batch:** Implement as an **automated queue** â€” the system generates pages one by one but automatically chains them, passing character reference from previous pages. This gives the FEEL of "generate all at once" with the reliability of sequential generation.

